StringWithMarkup.String: Fumes in air. Decomposes exothermically in water to give corrosive hydrochloric acid. Based on a scenario where the chemical is spilled into an excess of water (at least 5 fold excess of water), half of the maximum theoretical yield of Hydrogen Chloride gas will be created in 0.47 minutes.

Reference: NOAA; CAMEO Chemicals. Database of Hazardous Materials. Butyryl Chloride (141-75-3). Natl Ocean Atmos Admin, Off Resp Rest; NOAA Ocean Serv. Available from, as of June 20, 2017: http://cameochemicals.noaa.gov/

StringWithMarkup.String: Slowly dissolves in water with decomposition and formation of a weakly acidic solution. May react vigorously or explosively if mixed with diisopropyl ether or other ethers in the presence of trace amounts of metal salts.
